Incident Response > [T3]: Lab - Velociraptor: Deployment and Interface overview

Overview of Velociraptor deployment and interface

When deploying Velociraptor, you will need to run through three different tasks:

  1. Installing the Velociraptor server, which is presented in three different ways:
    • Self-Signed SSL - recommended for on-premises environments.
    • Cloud Deployment - recommended for easy deployments.
    • Instant Velociraptor - recommended if you want to install Velociraptor as a self-contained client and server on your local machine for testing purposes.
  2. Enrolling the clients, which can be done via:
    • Run clients interactively
    • Install using Custom MSI
    • Install the Client as a Service
    • Agentless Deployment
  3. Create a user and grant the user permission to access Velociraptor's console.

 

In your lab setup, we went with instant Velociraptor for the server part, allowing us to run both the server and agent on the same endpoint. 

For the client part, we went with option c and registered the agent as a service. 

In your lab, open Firefox, then visit https://127.0.0.1:8889. In case you are presented with a username and password, please use the following:

Username: student
Password: student 

From the dropdown next to Search clients input, choose "Show All."

Click on Client ID C.2b3a22f66b1c0ad6.

 

As you can see, it will list some information about the enrolled client as when the client got onboarded, the OS, and the hostname.


Heads up: Velociraptor uses a pre-defined artifact collection for this info which we will cover in the next point.
